body:
Summary

NJrat is a widely available Remote Access Tool. The tool was originally developed by a freelance coder with the alias of `njq8` in 2013. NJRat is commonly used as general spyware and to facilitate computer intrusions. NJRAT is often delivered via drive-by downloads and phishing emails. NJRat is most commonly used to target organizations in the middle east.

Response

When NJrat is suspected to be on the system the first step is to perform the following: * Gather the process list at the moment of the infection. This will provide the responder with a clear view of the process that might have caused the infection. Although NJrat process names can be highly customizable, they run as a standalone processes under the context of the user. * Take a memory image of the compromised host in order to investigate the infection further. Network indicators for this tool are very trivial to detect due to the lack of sophistication in its command and control protocol. The encoding scheme used for some of the parameters is base64. The Text below shows a sample of a command and control message. ``` 181.ll|'|'|SGFjS2VkXzhFODZBRDlD|'|'|PETER-PC|'|'|peter|'|'|16-08-29|'|'||'|'|Win 7 Ultimate SP1 x64|'|'|Yes|'|'|0.7d|'|'|..|'|'|Q2FwdHVyaW5nIGZyb20gTG9jYWwgQXJlYSBDb25uZWN0aW9uAA==|'|'|104.inf|'|'|SGFjS2VkDQoxOTIuMTY4LjEuMzU6NTU1Mg0KVEVNUA0Kc2VydmVyXzUuZXhlDQpUcnVlDQpUcnVlDQpUcnVlDQpGYWxzZQ== ``` Two methods of persistence can be easily chosen from the builder. The first method involves copying the binary to the following startup folder: ``` C:\Documents and Settings\user\Start Menu\Programs\Startup ``` The second method involves a registry key that stands out and can be easily discernible at plain sight. As seen in figure 2 the registry key name has the appearance of a 32 character alphanumeric value that resembles a checksum, but is not an md5 hash value. It also specifies the path where the malicious file is located. ``` Figure 2 ``` The builder offers several paths in which the malware can be installed. These paths are: ``` - %TEMP% - %AppData% - %UserProfile% - %AllUsersProfile% - %Windir% ``` The registry name also serves as the mutex in order to prevent similar copies to be active on the system. Responders can easily detect these entries and delete them from the system for mitigation.

Capabilities

NJrat offers a wide selection of features that might leave an easily detectable footprint in the system. These include: - Remote shell and interactive Remote Desktop capabilities. - Process manager, connection monitor, registry editor and file manager. - Execution of files and scripts. - Remote camera monitoring. - Remote microphone monitoring. - Keylogger. - Open chat. - Install, uninstall, update, restart, disconnect, rename server on demand. - Password stealer - Builder offers highly customization features for the c2 such as port number and persistence mechanisms. - Process protection. In case the user tries to terminate the process. NJrat will cause a blue screen.

Host Indicators

Systems infected with NJrat have several traces of host based indicators. These are: - Two persistence mechanisms that involve either a registry entry or modifications in the startup folder. The registry entries are created under the following hives ``` HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run HKCU\Software\32{characters}\[kl] ``` - Artifact files that might indicate keylogging activity. NJrat stores the keylogger data under the following registry key: ``` HKCU\Software\32{characters}\[kl] ``` - A copy of the binary is saved in the registry under the following registry key: ``` HKCU\Software\32{characters}\32{characters} ``` - Standalone infector file that performs consistent connections to the command and control server. Using tools like tcpview can easily detect suspicious connections. The location of the infector file is determined by where the victim downloaded the file to. Therefore its location varies. - Processes running NJrat tend to be standalone and can be easily identified via process listing. NJrat does not perform any type of process injection and the name of the binary can be pretty much any name. One of the tell signs is the lack of description and company name in the process details. A tool like process explorer can assist in identifying the malicious process. Figure 3 below shows process explorer in action ``` Figure 3 ```
